text: Not exactly too sure about the title of the film but the people behind John Wick are behind this so... I'm definitely curious. Plus I love the fact that Charlize Theron is actually showing off some bleeding. Something that I hate in action films is how some characters get beaten up but aren't seen any sign of wound. No shaky cam, no intense montage sequence... Plus Theron coming back to action since Mad Max: Fury Road is a good sign. If she can pull off her own identity instead of being a John Wick, then MAYBE it'll be more than a "female" action movie. She has to be an action hero, not a female action hero: she has to be on par with what's already established in cinemas. That's TRUE equality. But first, the movie will have to be good. If it's not, then she'll be a "John Wick" pretender. That's how it works. But female action heroes already have a bad reputation... no matter what people think of Resident Evil (the movies) and Underworld.

text: To everyone saying it's impossible for her to be able to do this kind of stuff either because she's a woman or because she isn't muscular enough: Something important to remember is that strength isn't always defined by big muscles. Big muscles can do great things but sometimes people don't know how to use them. Put someone who lifts weights with no fighting experience in a fight and they probably won't do very well because muscle does not equal agility. If you look at Bruce Lee movies, you will notice that there aren't a lot of cuts made in his fight scenes - that is because he is ACTUALLY fighting. He actually has the agility and skills to make those quick movements and think fast. Most actors today don't have to do that because they can cheat it with lots of cuts and stuff. And look at Bruce Lee. Did he have huge, rippling muscles? Nope. He was toned, but he didn't look anything like Mark Wahlberg.   TL;DR  Having big muscles doesn't mean you know how to use em!

text: From an analytical perspective, the fact that she is a woman facing men more than half her size makes the fight more realistic. The term "femme fatale" comes from the belief that because women are smaller, then they must be weaker. Obviously this isn't true. But it is a common belief among most people,  especially men who have witnessed smaller men dominate larger men. Her moves appear slower because they are, and her fighting style capitalizes on that. Because she is a woman, and smaller, her adversaries are more likely to underestimate her and assume her attacks won't hurt them. Knowing this, she takes the time to put real force behind her attacks and ultimately gain the upper hand. We are all still human. Obviously size matters, but if you put enough force and enough will behind an object, a fist, a kick, coupled with timing, you can do some damage. It's just physics.

text: Yeah I didn't like this film. Maybe I just didn't understand it I dunno (I feel like the movies that get the best reviews by critics are the ones that I simply can't relate to for whatever reason whereas the movies that get the worst reviews, I actually like those). I had no idea what was going on the entire time. The plot was nonexistent, the pacing was really slow, the dialogue was sketchy, the acting was stilted, there were too many scenes of the main character smoking & drinking (as if that's the only thing that makes you a badass) and there weren't enough fight scenes (I went into this thinking it was gonna be like a Fast & Furious movie with non-stop action. Boy was I wrong! And since a lot of people are comparing this film to John Wick, it makes me not want to watch John Wick because that film is probably just as bad). I really wanted to like this movie because we need another epic female action flick, plus, Charlize Theron is an amazing actress. But let's face it, Angelina Jolie is like the only female who's actually good at making action flicks (plus, she probably has better screenwriters and directors for her films). Every other actress pales comparison. Anyway, I kinda regret paying to see Atomic Blonde but at the same time "Pride and Prejudice and Zombies" was even worse (as was the  "Carrie" remake a few years ago and "Hercules" with The Rock) so it's not like Atomic Blonde was the worst movie I paid to see (plus, I recently paid to see "Wish Upon" which was cheesy but I knew that going in. I purposefully paid to see a cheesy teen horror movie and I'm doing it again with "Polaroid" later this month. With Atomic Blonde, as well as PPZ, Carrie & Hercules, I actually expected it to be good but it just wasn't).

What's not to love? A-/B+
